definition.value: This is an AE which is damage to the injection site caused by an external force.
This is an AE which is a injection site state of inflammation or painful reaction to allergy or cell-lining damage.
This is an AE which refers to accumulation of fluid in an anatomic injection site joint space, usually without loculation.
This is an AE which is redness of the injection site joint skin or mucous membranes, caused by hyperemia (increased blood flow) in superficial capillaries.

This is an AE which is a procedure used in the treatment of inflammatory joint conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, gout, tendinitis, bursitis, Carpal Tunnel Syndrome, and occasionally osteoarthritis.

This is an AE which is part of the complex biological response of injection site joint tissues to harmful stimuli, such as pathogens, damaged cells, or irritants,and is a protective response involving immune cells, blood vessels, and molecular mediators.
This is an AE which is a distressing feeling on the injection site joint often caused by intense or damaging stimuli.
This is an AE which refers a transient abnormal enlargement of injection site joint area not caused by a tumor.
This is an AE which refers a somewhat high temperature on the injection site joint.

This is an AE which is a type of injury which happens relatively quickly such as in the injection site in which skin is torn, cut, or punctured (an open wound), or where blunt force trauma causes a contusion (a closed wound).
This is an AE which is a lack of muscle strength in the injection site.
This is an AE which is a form of cell injury in the injection site which results in the premature death of cells in living tissue by autolysis.
This is an AE which is injury to nervous tissue in the injection site.
This is an AE which refers a small aggregation of cells in the injection site.
This is an AE which is the build-up of fluid in the injection site tissue.
This is an AE which is a pale color of the injection site skin.
This is an AE which is a small, well-defined bump in the injection site skin.
This is an AE which is an abnormal sensation of the injection site skin (tingling, pricking, chilling, burning, numbness) with no apparent physical cause.
This is an AE which refers a type of cutaneous condition in the injection site .
This is an AE which is any medical condition that affects the integumentary system in the injection site .
This is an AE which is an area of fibrous tissue that replaces normal skin after an injury in the injection site tissue.
This is an AE which is small dilated blood vessels that can occur near the surface of the injection site skin or mucous membranes, measuring between 0.5 and 1 millimeter in diameter.
This is an AE which is a group of disorders that destroy blood vessels by inflammation on the injection site.
This is an AE which is redness of the instillation site skin or mucous membranes, caused by hyperemia (increased blood flow) in superficial capillaries.
This is an AE which is an abnormal sensation of the instillation site skin (tingling, pricking, chilling, burning, numbness) with no apparent physical cause.
This is an AE which refers a liquid-filled cavity under the instillation site epidermis, commonly called a blister.
This is an AE which is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the joint.
This is an AE which is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the muscle.
This is an AE which is a rare complication of acute parotitis in children.
This is an AE which refers an abscess in the psoas muscle of the abdomen may be caused by lumbar tuberculosis.
This is an AE which is the most common symptom is fever, followed by abdominal pain and a tender mass on palpation of the left upper quadrant of the abdomen.
This is an AE which is an abscess located in the subcutaneous tissue (also hypodermis).
This is an AE which is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the body caused  by streptococcal.
This is an AE which is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the subdural.

This is an AE which is a condition that typically presents as collection of pus in the space between the periorbital and the lamina papyracea as a result of the migration and spread of an infection, such as sinusitis and ethmoiditis.
This is an AE which is a neoplasm or tumor of the thyroid.
This is an AE which is an unfavorable result of a disease, health condition, or treatment such after vaccination.
This is an AE which is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the vaccination site.
This is an AE which is a vaccination site state of controlled, temporary loss of sensation or awareness that is induced for medical purposes.
This is an AE which is the partial or complete wasting away of a part of the vaccination site.

This is an AE which is a type of hematoma of vaccination site, the most common cause being capillaries damaged by trauma, causing localized bleeding that extravasates into the surrounding interstitial tissues.
This is an AE which is a bacterial infection involving the inner layers of the vaccination site skin.
This is an AE which is a closed sac on the vaccination site, having a distinct envelope and division compared with the nearby tissue.
This is an AE which is a medical condition in which there is local or more generalized decrease in normal lubrication of the vaccination site skin or mucous membranes.
This is an AE which defines as an unpleasant, abnormal sense of touch on the vaccination site.
This is an AE which refers to a broad range of conditions that begin as spongiotic dermatitis and may progress to a lichenified stage on the vaccination site.
This is an AE which is redness of the vaccination site skin or mucous membranes, caused by hyperemia (increased blood flow) in superficial capillaries.
This is an AE which is a slough or piece of dead tissue that is cast off from the surface of the vaccination site  skin.
This is an AE which aims to remove dead skin from the vaccination site tissue.
This is an AE which is an aggregation of macrophages that forms in response to chronic inflammation on the vaccination site.
